# How I Build Team Culture

Culture isn't a ping pong table. It's what happens when no one is watching — how decisions get made, how people treat each other when things are hard, whether someone will tell the truth in a room full of people who don't want to hear it.

## What I build toward

**High trust, high candor.** I want a team where people say what they actually think — in retros, in design reviews, in 1:1s. That doesn't happen by accident. It happens because I model it, reward it, and protect the people who do it.

**Psychological safety with accountability.** These are not opposites. Safety means you can raise a problem without fear. Accountability means we actually fix it. I want both.

**Credit given publicly, corrections given privately.** When someone does something great, I say so — to the team, to leadership, wherever it's appropriate. When someone misses, we talk about it directly, not in a group setting.

**Curiosity over certainty.** I'd rather have a team that asks good questions than one that pretends to have all the answers. We learn out loud here.

## What I won't tolerate

- Undermining teammates, publicly or privately
- Hiding bad news until it becomes a crisis
- Coasting on past performance
- Treating anyone — on the team or outside it — as less than

## On remote and distributed teams

I've led distributed teams across time zones. Culture on a distributed team requires more intention, not less. That means clear async communication norms, deliberate relationship-building, and making sure no one feels like a second-class participant because of where they sit.
